Then, the quenching effects of HS− at different concentrations on the NCD fluorescence intensity was investigated. Fig. 4
                        a shows that the NCD fluorescence intensity decreases with increasing HS− concentration until it is quenched at the HS− concentration of 100 μM. Further, Fig. 4b shows the linear relationship between the NCD fluorescence intensity and HS− concentration in the range of 2–55 μM (R2 = 0.99553). We calculate the LOD value (according to “3σ/k”) to be 50.11 nM (σ is the standard deviation of the blank solution measured fifteen times, and k is the slope from Fig. 4b) [31]. Compared with other HS−detection probes, NCDs shows a wider detection range of HS− concentrations (Table 1
                        ).
